Question 1
The link layer is implemented in the network interface card as well as in software (mostly at the operating system level).

  True 

Question 2
The network interface card consists of the controller and components that deal with the physical transmissions of signals.
  True 
 
Question 3
With Hot Potato Routing a certain IP prefix is routed to a Next-Hop router on a least cost path.
  True 

Question 4
In IPv4, if a datagram gets fragmented, it gets reassembled at the next hop router, i.e. the one that comes right after the router that fragmented the datagram.
  False 
 
Question 5
Single bit parity checks can detect any combination of two bit errors.
  False 
 
Question 6
Internet check summing is not implemented at the link layer protocols, like Ethernet.
  True 
 
Question 7
ASs are addressed using IP addresses.
  False 
 
Question 8
The cyclic redundency check as the most powerful error detection technique in the Internet.
  True 
 
Question 9
The Internet is a "network of networks". As a consequence, IPv4 addresses have two parts, i.e. a network address part and a host address part.
  True 
 
Question 10
Link layer protocols provide reliability only in environments, where there are high error rates.
  True 
 
Question 11
Broadcast links: Ethernet employs a algorithm called "linear exponential backoff" to determine the wait time after a collision has occurred.
  False 
 
Question 12
At the link layer, to (forward-)correct errors, the cost in terms of overhead information is higher, compared to error detection.
Correct!
  True 
 
Question 13
The link layer allows for "piecing together" and end-toend path by potentially many individual links.
Correct!
  True 
 
Question 14
A router's forwarding table maps IP address postfixes to output ports.
  False 
 
Question 15
IP addresses are associated with network interfaces. That means that routers have to have several IP addresses.
Correct!
  True 
 
Question 16
The problem with Inter-AS routing algorithm is that they don't take into account adminstrative autonomy of ISPs.
  True 
 
Question 17
Two-dimentional parity checks can detect any combination of two bit errors.
Correct!
  True  
 
Question 18
To correct errors in packets of information, you may either detect the error and retransmit the packets or employ forward error correction.
Correct!
  True 
 
Question 19
The network layer provides nothing more than a "best effort" service.
Correct!
  True 
 
Question 20
The ping service is used to see if a host with a given IP address is reachable. It is implemented by way of ICMP messages.
Correct!
  True  
 
Question 21
While forward error correction has considerable overhead, there are special applications, like communication to Mars robots, where it is used.
Correct!
  True 
 
Question 22
Intra-AS routing is routing between networks in the sense of IP-defined networks.
  True 
 
Question 23
The problem with Intra-AS routing algorithm is that they don't take into account adminstrative autonomy of ISPs.
  False 
 
Question 24
In the network layer, "forwarding" is the router-local action of transferring packets from a router's input links to its output links, based on entries of its forwarding table.
  True 
 
Question 25
In IPv4, the IP header contains two IP addresses, that together are 64 bits long.
  True 
 
Question 26
For broadcast links at the link layer, CSMA/CD has similarities with TDM - we may call the former "statistical TDM".
Correct!
  True 
 
Question 27
In IPv4, if datagrams get fragmented, the Identification field determines the order of the fragments.
  False 
 
Question 28
In the network layer, because of the long timescale, the Control Plane is implemented in software.
Correct!
  True 
 
Question 29
The lookup of IP address prefixes in forwarding tables works according to "leftmost longest matching".
  True 
 
Question 30
Broadcast links: assume that a network interface card senses that the medium is open and thus starts sending out a signal. Even then a collision with the signal of another network interface card may occur.
  True 
